{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed; unchanged files are skipped.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failures usually occur at the PR-change discovery boundary (git diff/GitHub PR file list, checkout depth, rename handling, path normalization). In-process mocks can hide these mismatches.","test_description":"Run the lint step in a GitHub-Action-like job against a real test repo and PR with known changed and unchanged files. Verify analyzer inputs include only PR-changed paths (including edge cases like renamed files) and that unchanged files never appear in scan logs/results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Grouping correctness depends on wiring parser output, severity mapping, and comment rendering. A single-function unit test can miss enum/contract mismatches across modules.","test_description":"Feed multi-severity linter outputs through the real aggregation + comment-construction pipeline and assert the generated PR comment body contains distinct error/warning/info sections with the right findings in each. Stub the final post call only.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request touching 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Timeout behavior is runtime/OS/subprocess dependent (I/O, process startup, CPU contention) and cannot be trusted from mocked or purely in-process tests.","test_description":"Execute the full lint step in CI (or a close runner equivalent) on a synthetic PR with 200 representative files; measure wall-clock end-to-end time and fail if total duration exceeds a safety threshold below 10 minutes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the linter process crashes on one malformed file, remaining files are still analyzed and results are posted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure boundary is real process-crash handling (non-zero exit, signal, stderr truncation, partial output), which mocks often sanitize away.","test_description":"Use a test linter binary/script that crashes on a specific malformed file but succeeds on others. Run the pipeline over mixed files and verify it continues scanning remaining files, reports surviving findings, and still posts a PR comment with crash notice plus collected results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.77,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules are deduplicated in output.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Dedup failures often come from cross-module normalization differences (path format, line indexing, rule identity) rather than a single pure function.","test_description":"Run real rule-output ingestion (or fixture outputs from multiple rules) through normalization + dedup + formatting pipeline where two rules emit same file/line/message. Assert exactly one output finding is emitted for that logical location.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
